<p>The book also breaks little new ground - the major thesis that represents a contribution to the field, as far as I could tell, is â€œwho needs causal evidence when you can use correlational evidence based on ALL the data.â€ There are a couple of major issues with that, but the most easily identified is that the big data sources that the authors are talking about donâ€™t necessarily include all the data - so itâ€™s easy to jump to correlational patterns that donâ€™t match or explain parts of the dataset that arenâ€™t included.</p>

<p>Additionally, companies that rely on correlational data open themselves up to manipulation from anyone who understands causal factors in the data. For example, Mayer-Schnonberger and Cukier cite predicting airline prices as an example of not needing to understand the underlying causal factors if given enough correlational data. Â However, an airline could pretty easily manipulate any service that relies purely on correlational data to determine when prices will be the highest. This doesnâ€™t break their argument, of course - certainly, correlational data may often be good enough. But this isÂ symptomaticÂ of the authorâ€™s general lack of engagement with the consequences of the trends they suggest, and for a book that is rehashing old (in Internet years) territory, thatâ€™s a pretty bad thing.Â </p>

